<DocsLayout title="ctx_tree — Project Map" description="Token-efficient directory listings with file counts.">
  <p>
    <code>ctx_tree</code> generates compact project structure maps using indentation instead of
    Unicode box-drawing characters. Each directory shows a file count for quick orientation.
  </p>

  <h2>Parameters</h2>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>string</td><td>No</td><td>Directory to list (default: project root)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>depth</code></td><td>number</td><td>No</td><td>Maximum depth (default: 3)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h2>Example</h2>
  <pre><code>ctx_tree --depth 2

→ lean-ctx/rust/
    src/ (22)
      core/ (9)
      tools/ (8)
      patterns/ (5)
    examples/ (1)
    Cargo.toml
    README.md
  [64 tok saved (34%)]</code></pre>

  <h2>Why It Saves Tokens</h2>
  <p>
    Traditional directory listings use Unicode box-drawing characters (<code>├──</code>, <code>└──</code>)
    which consume 3-4 tokens each. lean-ctx uses simple indentation (1 token per level), and shows
    file counts per directory instead of listing every file. For large projects, this saves 30-50% tokens.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
